Homelessness in Seattle

This is our report on homelessness in Seattle. We got our data from here. The data was collected by the Regional Homelessness Authority, a legislation approved by the Seattle City Council that oversees the funding, policy, and services for dealing with the homelessness issue throughout the county. They do a yearly count of the homeless population in King County. The data was generated partly by them, and partly by other organizations like the Puget Sound Regional Council and the Seattle King County Coalition on Homelessness. Its a relational database, and it has 13 different tables, all focusing on different topics about homelessness.

Something interesting we found about this table was that the race / ethnicity with the highest percentage was Multiple races except for 2015, which was Multiple races. The most common duration of being homeless was 1 year or more, which was always above 50% of the total homeless population. The region with the highest homeless population was always Seattle for the last 4 years. Seattle saw a sharp increase from 0.35 in 2017 to 0.67 in 2020.

A question that we had in relation to Homelessness in King was relating to the demographics of the homeless population. We wanted to see what races made up what percentages of the homeless population. More specifically, what specific race had the biggest population of homelessness

Chart 1 According to the chart, it looks like the biggest race demmographic of homeless people is people who identify as White.

Another question in relation to Homelessness is how the leading causes have changed over the years. From 2017-2020, we looked at what the leading cause of homelessness was for each year.

Chart 2 Where does unsheltered homelessness occur the most in King County? This chart shows the unsheltered homeless count by region in King County from 2017-2020. This chart helps to see patterns of how many unsheltered homeless people there have been over the years and how it has changed in each region, as well as how that number of people compares to other regions. It is clear that over the last few years, Seattle is the region that has consistently had the most unsheltered homeless people. It can be seen in the chart that there is a much smaller gap between all of the other regions, with Seattle largely above all the other regions in count.

Chart 3 In 2020, the leading cause was Lost Jobs. In 2019, the leading cause was when an argument with a friend/family member occurred. In 2018 and 2017, the leading cause was when friends or family could no longer afford to or refused to host.
